3. AIC dredge for sub-models

For the core, disturbance, and configuration models we will run a dredge at each spatial scale and find the most parsimonious model at the best scale for each model type. Then, well choose the overall best model of all spatial scales based on the lowest AIC

3.1. NATURAL sub-model

For the core model (natural features), variables are: conifer forest, broadleaf forest, mixed forest, shrub, and grassland.

  • took out broadleaf because correlated
natural_results <- purrr::map_dfr(seq(250, 5000, by = 250), ~{
  
  cat("\r\r Dredging `NATURAL` sub-models at spatial scale:", .x, "m")
  
  # Subset the data based on the current buffer distance
  data_subset <- data_scaled %>%
    
    filter(buffer_dist == .x)
  
  # Fit the initial model for the current buffer distance
  model_natural <- glmmTMB(cbind(red_squirrel, absent_red_squirrel) ~ 
                           lc_coniferous +
                           lc_mixed + 
                           lc_shrub +
                           lc_grassland +
                           #(1|site) + 
                           (1|array), 
                         data = data_subset, 
                         family = "binomial", 
                         na.action = na.fail)

  # Perform dredge selection based on AIC
  dredge_natural <- MuMIn::dredge(model_natural, 
                                  rank = AIC, 
                                  evaluate = TRUE, 
                                  trace = FALSE) %>%
    
    as.data.frame(.) %>%
    
    select(-`disp((Int))`) %>%
  
    rename_with(~ gsub("cond\\(|disp\\(|\\)|\\(", "", .)) %>%

    rename(intercept = `Int`,
           delta_subset = delta) %>%
    
    mutate(buffer_dist = .x)
  
  return(dredge_natural)
  }
  ) %>%
  
  mutate(delta = AIC - min(AIC)) %>%
  
  arrange(delta)

3.2. COMP sub-model

For the disturbance model (anthropogenic features), variables are: seismic lines, linear (transmission and pipelines), roads, harvest blocks, well pads, and industrial features.

comp_results <- purrr::map_dfr(seq(250, 5000, by = 250), ~{
  
  cat("\r\r Dredging `COMP` sub-models at spatial scale:", .x, "m")

  # Subset the data based on the current buffer distance
  data_subset <- data_scaled %>%
    
    filter(buffer_dist == .x)
  
  # Fit the initial model for the current buffer distance
  model_comp <- glmmTMB(cbind(red_squirrel, absent_red_squirrel) ~ 
                           harvest +
                           pipe_trans + 
                           wells + 
                           roads +
                           osm_industrial + 
                           seismic +
                           #(1|site) + 
                           (1|array), 
                         data = data_subset, 
                         family = "binomial", 
                         na.action = na.fail)

  
  # Perform dredge selection based on AIC
  dredge_comp <- MuMIn::dredge(model_comp, 
                                  rank = AIC, 
                                  evaluate = TRUE, 
                                  trace = FALSE) %>%
    
    as.data.frame(.) %>%
    
    select(-`disp((Int))`) %>%
  
    rename_with(~ gsub("cond\\(|disp\\(|\\)|\\(", "", .)) %>%
    
    rename(intercept = `Int`,
           delta_subset = delta) %>%
    
    mutate(buffer_dist = .x)
  
  return(dredge_comp)
  }
  ) %>%
  
  mutate(delta = AIC - min(AIC)) %>%
  
  arrange(delta)

3.3. CONFIG sub-model

For the disturbance model (anthropogenic features), variables are: seismic lines, linear (transmission and pipelines), roads, harvest blocks, well pads, and industrial features.

config_results <- purrr::map_dfr(seq(250, 5000, by = 250), ~{
  
  cat("\r\r Dredging `CONFIG` sub-models at spatial scale:", .x, "m")

  # Subset the data based on the current buffer distance

    filter(buffer_dist == .x)

  model_config <- glmmTMB(cbind(red_squirrel, absent_red_squirrel) ~ 
                           veg_anthro_ed +
                           nonveg_anthro_ed + 
                           forest_cai_mn + 
                           #forest_tca +
                           #forest_cohesion + 
                           #(1|site) + 
                           (1|array),

                         family = "binomial", 
                         na.action = na.fail)

  # Perform dredge selection based on AIC

                                  rank = AIC, 
                                  evaluate = TRUE, 
                                  trace = FALSE) %>%
    
    as.data.frame(.) %>%
    
    select(-`disp((Int))`) %>%
  
    rename_with(~ gsub("cond\\(|disp\\(|\\)|\\(", "", .)) %>%
    
    rename(intercept = `Int`,
           delta_subset = delta) %>%
    
    mutate(buffer_dist = .x)
  
  return(dredge_config)
  }
  ) %>%
  
  mutate(delta = AIC - min(AIC)) %>%
  
  arrange(delta)

3.4. Save results

We will save the top predictors and the top spatial scale so that we dont need to re-run the dredge every time.

save(config_results, comp_results, natural_results, 
     comp_predictors, comp_buffer, natural_predictors, 
     natural_buffer, config_predictors, config_buffer, 
     file = "./data/processed/submodel_dredge_top_predictors_scales.RData")

4. Scale analysis

Another nice way to visualize our results for the scale analysis is to plot the model weight for the global sub-models at each scale.

Natural sub-model:

natural_scale <- purrr::map(seq(250, 5000, by = 250), ~{
  
  # Subset the data based on the current buffer distance
  data_subset <- data_scaled %>%
    
    filter(buffer_dist == .x)
  
  # Fit the initial model for the current buffer distance
  model_natural <- glmmTMB(cbind(red_squirrel, absent_red_squirrel) ~ 
                           lc_coniferous +
                           lc_mixed + 
                           lc_shrub +
                           lc_grassland +
                           #(1|site) + 
                           (1|array), 
                         data = data_subset, 
                         family = "binomial", 
                         na.action = na.fail)
  
  return(model_natural)
  }
  ) %>%
  
  set_names(as.character(seq(250, 5000, by = 250))) %>%
  
  MuMIn::model.sel(.) %>%
  
  mutate(buffer = as.numeric(rownames(.)),
         submodel = "NATURAL")

Anthro composition submodel:

comp_scale <- purrr::map(seq(250, 5000, by = 250), ~{
  
  # Subset the data based on the current buffer distance
  data_subset <- data_scaled %>%
    
    filter(buffer_dist == .x)

Configuration sub-model:

config_scale <- purrr::map(seq(250, 5000, by = 250), ~{
  
  # Subset the data based on the current buffer distance
  data_subset <- data_scaled %>%

                           veg_anthro_ed +

5.2. Fit the models

Now lets fit our models and compete the combination of submodels against each other according to our ecological hypotheses:

# Null model
m_null <- glmmTMB::glmmTMB(cbind(red_squirrel, absent_red_squirrel) ~ 1 +
                             
                     (1|array), 
                     data = data_final_scaled, 
                     family = "binomial")

comp_predictors

Lets put these into our model. Roads and well sites are quite correlated at this scale so we will remove roads from the models. There was also weak separation between models with/without osm_industrial in the dredging step so we will take this out too.

# Natural + comp model

Recall the configuration predictors:

config_predictors

Check dispersion:

performance::check_overdispersion(top_model)
## # Overdispersion test
## 
##  dispersion ratio =   2.219
##           p-value = < 0.001
## Overdispersion detected.

The model is overdispersed. Variance is much higher than the mean which violates an assumption of the bernoilli distribution. A zero inflated bernoulli (ZIB) might be more appropriate. Re-binning the data into monthly occurrence frequency might also help eliminate a lot of the zeros that are (likely) the cause of this.

  ggplot(., aes(x = term)) +

    geom_line(size = 0.5) +  # Set lines to black

ggeffects::ggpredict(top_model, 
                              terms = c("veg_anthro_ed [all]",
